{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01J5397soqZsg3FnbQvhQFVP","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# `bob_tools.planfile`: deterministic PLAN.md handling\n2\t\n3\tStatus: draft for discussion. Scope: define a single library that owns\n4\tPLAN.md syntax, parsing, serialization, and operations across McLoop,\n5\tDuplo, and human editors, so that PLAN.md handling stops being\n6\tLLM-mediated and starts being deterministic.\n7\t\n8\tThis document is structured for cold review. Every claim about\n9\texisting behavior cites the file and function it was verified against.\n10\tEvery proposed addition is marked as such. Open questions are flagged\n11\texplicitly at the end.\n12\t\n13\t---\n14\t\n15\t## 1. Problem\n16\t\n17\tPLAN.md is currently produced, parsed, and mutated by three actors:\n18\tMcLoop's runner, Duplo's planner, and humans editing directly.\n19\tMcLoop has a real parser\n20\t(`mcloop/checklist.py:parse`, line 151); Duplo writes through an\n21\tLLM and a partial postprocess; humans edit freely. The three actors\n22\tdo not share a single contract, and the LLM-mediated paths have\n23\tproduced corruption that McLoop's parser explicitly refuses to\n24\tauto-fix (`PlanCorruptionError`, `mcloop/checklist.py:27`; the\n25\tfail-closed message is assembled at lines 142-148).\n26\t\n27\tThe goal is to make PLAN.md handling deterministic without removing\n28\tthe human-editable property. Concretely:\n29\t\n30\t- One library owns parsing, serialization, validation, and operations.\n31\t- McLoop and Duplo call the library; the LLM never owns plan structure.\n32\t- Humans may still hand-edit, but tools refuse to \"best-effort\" parse\n33\t  malformed input. Errors are line/column-located.\n34\t- The library coexists with the Plan Ledger\n35\t  (`bob_tools/ledger/`); it is not a replacement for the audit/event\n36\t  surface that already exists.\n37\t\n38\t## 2. Current state (audit)\n39\t\n40\tThis section records what is already on disk, with citations, so the\n41\tdesign does not invent state that already exists or contradict\n42\tbehavior that the runner depends on.\n43\t\n44\t### 2.1 McLoop's parser\n45\t\n46\t`mcloop/checklist.py` is the working parser. It defines:\n47\t\n48\t- `CHECKBOX_RE = r\"^(\\s*)- \\[([ xX!])\\] (.+)$\"` (line 9). Four markers\n49\t  are admitted: space (todo), `x`/`X` (done), `!` (failed).\n50\t- `STAGE_RE = r\"^#+\\s+.*?\\b(?:stage|phase)\\s+(\\d+)\\b\"` (line 12). Any\n51\t  heading level whose title contains `Stage N` or `Phase N` is a\n52\t  section header. The `\\d+` is mandatory — bare digits only.\n53\t- `BUGS_RE = r\"^#+\\s+Bugs\\s*$\"` (line 14). Any heading level titled\n54\t  exactly `Bugs` is the bug-priority section.\n55\t- Four operational tags: `[USER]` (`_USER_TAG`, line 22),\n56\t  `[BATCH]` (`_BATCH_TAG`, line 23), `[AUTO:<action>]`\n57\t  (`_AUTO_TAG_RE`, line 24), and `[RULEDOUT]` as a non-task\n58\t  indent-attached line (handled in `parse`, lines 189-204).\n59\t- `PlanCorruptionError` (line 27) is raised on duplicate H1 titles,\n60\t  multiple `## Bugs` sections, or duplicate phase/stage numbers.\n61\t  Auto-fixing is deliberately not attempted (the docstring at line\n62\t  26 records the rationale).\n63\t\n64\tThe status enum is **three-valued**: `[ ] / [x] / [!]`. The `[USER]`\n65\ttoken is an orthogonal in-text tag, not a checkbox state.\n66\t`is_user_task` (line 627) substring-searches the task text.\n67\t\n68\t### 2.2 McLoop's execution semantics\n69\t\n70\t`mcloop/main.py:run_loop` consumes the parsed tree and dispatches on\n71\tthe tags:\n72\t\n73\t- `[AUTO:<action>]` tasks call `_handle_auto_task(label, action, args)`\n74\t  and are checked off automatically. The action vocabulary\n75\t  (`run_cli`, `run_gui`, `screenshot`, etc.) is interpreted by\n76\t  `mcloop/investigate_cmd.py`.\n77\t- `[USER]` tasks pause the run, print formatted instructions, and\n78\t  accept free-form text input. A failed `[USER]` verification files\n79\t  a new bug into BUGS.md and sets `terminal_failure`; the `[USER]`\n80\t  task itself stays unchecked for re-verification after the bug is\n81\t  fixed.\n82\t- `[BATCH]` parents collect consecutive unchecked children via\n83\t  `get_batch_children` (line 654) and run them as a single\n84\t  session. `[USER]` or `[AUTO:…]` children halt batch collection.\n85\t- `[RULEDOUT]` lines feed `get_eliminated(tasks, task)` whose result\n86\t  is appended to the task prompt as a \"RULED OUT APPROACHES\" block,\n87\t  suppressing repeat strategies (verified in\n88\t  `mcloop/runner.py`, lines 376-385, 422-431, and 482-491).\n89\t\n90\t`find_next` (line 434) implements the actionable-task algorithm:\n91\t\n92\t1. Bug tasks (under `## Bugs`) have absolute priority.\n93\t2. Otherwise, only tasks in the first incomplete stage are returned.\n94\t3. Failed subtasks (`[!]`) block all later siblings under the same\n95\t   parent (implicit sequential dependency,\n96\t   `_search_tasks`, lines 369-376).\n97\t4. A failed child prevents parent completion\n98\t   (`_auto_check_parents`, lines 730-756).\n99\t5. Auto-check parent when all children are done.\n100\t\n101\t`clear_failed_markers` (line 593) resets `[!]` back to `[ ]` on\n102\t`--retry`, anchored to checkbox syntax so prose containing the\n103\tliteral `- [!]` is not corrupted (lines 607-610).\n104\t\n105\t### 2.3 The Plan Ledger\n106\t\n107\t`bob_tools/ledger/` is already shipped and integrated into McLoop:\n108\t\n109\t- `bob_tools/ledger/SCHEMA.md` defines the on-disk format\n110\t  (`PLAN.events.jsonl`, append-only, one JSON object per line,\n111\t  envelope with `event_id` UUIDv7, `seq`, `writer_id`, `run_id`,\n112\t  `payload`).\n113\t- `mcloop/main.py` imports from `mcloop.ledger_config`,\n114\t  `mcloop.ledger_emit`, `mcloop.ledger_pause` and calls\n115\t  `_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(...))` after every task in\n116\t  the standard code-edit success/failure path. Exit code 5 is\n117\t  reserved for ledger-induced hard stops (`HardStop`, `main.py`,\n118\t  lines 218-244).\n119\t- `mcloop/ledger_config.py` gates the ledger with, in precedence\n120\t  order, CLI flags, `MCLOOP_NO_PLAN_LEDGER` /\n121\t  `MCLOOP_NO_AUTO_REAUTHOR`, `.orchestra/config.json`, and finally\n122\t  auto-detection of `<project>/.duplo/ledger/` (lines 1-17 and\n123\t  70-142).\n124\t- `mcloop/ledger_pause.py` evaluates thresholds after settlement and\n125\t  either returns no pause, invokes Duplo reauthor, or raises\n126\t  `HardStop`. It is explicitly fail-closed: failed reauthor leaves\n127\t  PLAN.md unchanged and records only the triggering crossing on the\n128\t  ledger (lines 1-22 and 297-420). Planfile does not need a separate\n129\t  \"paused state\" check; the settle/evaluate path already owns that\n130\t  decision.\n131\t- The ledger's status model is **richer than the parser's**:\n132\t  `pending | active | completed | abandoned | superseded | split |\n133\t  merged | blocked | provisional` (SCHEMA.md \"Phase status enum\").\n134\t- `TaskOutcome` (in `mcloop/ledger_emit.py:TaskOutcome`) carries\n135\t  `success`, `abandoned`, `summary`, `changed_files`,\n136\t  `failure_kind`, `transcript_ref`. The `failure_kind` field\n137\t  records `\"commit_failed\"`, `\"max_retries_exceeded\"`, etc.\n138\t\n139\t### 2.4 Phase identity in the ledger today\n140\t\n141\t`mcloop/ledger_emit.py` resolves phase IDs from PLAN.md via two\n142\tregexes:\n143\t\n144\t```python\n145\t_PHASE_HEADER_RE = re.compile(\n146\t    r\"^##\\s+Phase\\s+(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+):\\s+(?P<title>.+?)\\s*$\"\n147\t)\n148\t_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE = re.compile(\n149\t    r\"<!--\\s*phase_id\\s*:\\s*(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+)\\s*-->\"\n150\t)\n151\t```\n152\t\n153\t`find_explicit_phase_id_for_task(plan_text, task_label)` iterates\n154\tline by line. A line matching `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` sets\n155\t`current_phase_id`. A line containing the `task_label` as a\n156\tsubstring returns the current `current_phase_id`. A line matching\n157\t`_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE` updates `current_phase_id` for subsequent\n158\ttasks.\n159\t\n160\t`resolve_phase_id(plan_path, task_label, ordinal_index)` implements\n161\tthe explicit-required / ordinal-degraded contract. When the\n162\texplicit lookup yields nothing, `ordinal_index` maps to the n-th\n163\tphase header found. When that path runs, `record_phase_id_fallback`\n164\tprints a stderr warning and emits a `finding_observed` event tagged\n165\t`degraded`.\n166\t\n167\t### 2.5 The format incompatibility\n168\t\n169\tMcLoop's `STAGE_RE` requires `\\bphase\\s+\\d+\\b` — bare digits after\n170\t\"phase\". The ledger's `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` accepts\n171\t`[A-Za-z0-9_]+` after \"Phase\". The following table shows what each\n172\theading produces:\n173\t\n174\t| Heading                                            | McLoop STAGE_RE     | Ledger header regex             |\n175\t|----------------------------------------------------|---------------------|---------------------------------|\n176\t| `## Phase 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | matches, `phase_id=\"1\"`         |\n177\t| `## Phase phase_001: Core`                         | **does not match**  | matches, `phase_id=\"phase_001\"` |\n178\t| `## Stage 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | does not match                  |\n179\t| `## Stage 1: Core` + `<!-- phase_id: phase_001 -->`| matches (stage 1)   | matches via comment             |\n180\t\n181\tOnly the dual-line form satisfies both regexes today **and**\n182\tdelivers a stable string phase_id distinct from the ordinal. The\n183\tsingle-heading `## Phase phase_001:` form breaks McLoop's stage\n184\tdetection.\n185\t\n186\tA second-order consequence: a hypothetical `## Phase 1: ...` heading\n187\twould match both regexes, but the ledger would derive\n188\t`phase_id=\"1\"` from it. The current Duplo PLAN.md uses H1 phase\n189\theadings (`# Phase 1: ...`), which McLoop's `STAGE_RE` accepts but\n190\tthe ledger header regex does not. In both cases, the stable-ID\n191\tmigration cost is one `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->` line per phase,\n192\twith no rewrite of the visible heading.\n193\t\n194\t### 2.6 PLAN.md / ledger directionality\n195\t\n196\t`run_loop`'s success path calls `check_off(active_file, task)` to\n197\twrite `[x]` to PLAN.md *first*, then calls\n198\t`_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))` which emits\n199\ta `commit_landed` event as audit evidence of what PLAN.md already\n200\trecords. PLAN.md is the writable surface; the ledger is the\n201\tappend-only witness. Hand-edits flow PLAN.md → ledger, never the\n202\treverse.\n203\t\n204\t## 3. Architecture\n205\t\n206\t### 3.1 Library placement\n207\t\n208\t```\n209\tbob/\n210\t  bob_tools/\n211\t    ledger/       # already exists; owns events + projected state\n212\t    planfile/     # NEW; owns PLAN.md syntax + canonicalization\n213\t      model.py\n214\t      parser.py\n215\t      renderer.py\n216\t      operations.py\n217\t      fileio.py\n218\t      cli.py\n219\t      tests/\n220\t```\n221\t\n222\tThe two libraries are peers. They cross at exactly two values:\n223\t\n224\t- `phase_id`: written and read by `planfile` via headings and\n225\t  `<!-- phase_id: ... -->` comments; consumed by `ledger` in event\n226\t  payloads.\n227\t- `task_label`: computed by `planfile` from position and stable IDs;\n228\t  resolved to `phase_id` (and, when stable task IDs land, to\n229\t  `task_id`) by the McLoop settle hook.\n230\t\n231\t`mcloop.checklist` becomes a thin compatibility wrapper or\n232\tdisappears once callers migrate. `mcloop.plan_split` and Duplo's\n233\tplanner write through `planfile`.\n234\t\n235\t### 3.2 Function inventory (proposed)\n236\t\n237\tPure operations on typed objects:\n238\t\n239\t```\n240\tparse_plan(text)               -> Plan | PlanSyntaxError\n241\trender_plan(plan)              -> str\n242\tvalidate_plan(plan)            -> None | PlanValidationError\n243\tcanonicalize(text)             -> str\n244\tmigrate(plan)                  -> Plan\n245\tnext_tasks(plan, limit=1)      -> list[Task]\n246\tcomplete_task(plan, task_id, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\n247\tfail_task(plan, task_id, reason, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\n248\treset_task(plan, task_id)      -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\n249\tadd_task(plan, phase_id, text, deps=(), parent_id=None) -> Plan\n250\treplace_phase(plan, phase_id, new_phase) -> Plan\n251\tresolve_task_context(plan, task_label_or_id) -> {phase_id, task_id, label}\n252\tcheck_consistency(plan, events) -> None | PlanInconsistencyError\n253\t```\n254\t\n255\tFile operations wrap those with locking and atomic writes:\n256\t\n257\t```\n258\tload(path) -> Plan\n259\tsave(path, plan) -> None\n260\tupdate(path, operation) -> Plan\n261\t```\n262\t\n263\tImplementation rule: only `parse_plan` and `render_plan` touch text.\n264\tEverything else operates on typed objects.\n265\t\n266\tThe split between `canonicalize` and `migrate`:\n267\t\n268\t- `canonicalize(text)` is lossless formatting: parse the input,\n269\t  re-render in canonical form. Does **not** assign IDs or add\n270\t  phase-id comments. Input that already has IDs round-trips through\n271\t  `canonicalize` unchanged; input without IDs is rendered without\n272\t  IDs (compatibility output).\n273\t- `migrate(plan) -> Plan` mutates identity: assigns `T-NNNNNN:` IDs\n274\t  to tasks that have none, adds `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->`\n275\t  comments to phases that have none. Otherwise leaves the plan\n276\t  unchanged. Identity assignment is not formatting and must be\n277\t  explicit, not folded into a \"format\" operation.\n278\t- `bob-plan fmt PATH` is the composition: parse, migrate, save.\n279\t  ```python\n280\t  plan = parse_plan(text)\n281\t  plan = migrate(plan)\n282\t  save(path, plan)\n283\t  ```\n284\t\n285\tMutation operations return a tuple of Settlements rather than a\n286\tsingle one. A direct completion that also auto-checks a parent\n287\treturns `(direct_settlement, derived_no_event_settlement)` — explicit\n288\tand testable. Callers do not infer derived state by diffing Plans.\n289\tFor tasks with no derived effects the tuple has one element.\n290\t\n291\t## 4. Canonical syntax\n292\t\n293\tThe grammar is a strict subset of GFM Markdown. McLoop's existing\n294\tsyntax is the floor; the only **additions** are stable IDs and the\n295\toptional `<!-- phase_id: -->` comment (which the ledger already\n296\trecognizes).\n297\t\n298\t### 4.1 Example\n299\t\n300\t```markdown\n301\t<!-- bob-plan-format: 1 -->\n302\t\n303\t# Project Name\n304\t\n305\tProject prose is allowed here, before the first phase heading.\n306\t\n307\t## Stage 1: Core\n308\t<!-- phase_id: phase_001 -->\n309\t\n310\tPhase prose is allowed here, before the first task.\n311\t\n312\t- [ ] T-000001: [BATCH] Markdown checklist parser\n313\t  - [ ] T-000002: Parse tasks from markdown checkboxes\n314\t  - [ ] T-000003: Find the next unchecked item\n315\t    [RULEDOUT] Do not identify tasks by text alone; duplicate text is legal.\n316\t  - [x] T-000004: Check off completed items in the file\n317\t- [ ] T-000005: [USER] Launch the app and confirm the main window appears\n318\t- [ ] T-000006: [AUTO:run_cli] mcloop --dry-run\n319\t- [!] T-000007: Fix failing import path\n320\t\n321\t### Manual verification\n322\t\n323\t- [ ] T-000008: Run the smoke test by hand\n324\t\n325\t## Bugs\n326\t\n327\t- [ ] T-000009: Crash on empty PLAN.md\n328\t```\n329\t\n330\t### 4.2 Productions\n331\t\n332\t```\n333\tPlan        ← Magic Preamble? PhaseOrBugs+ EOF\n334\tMagic       ← \"<!--\" WS? \"bob-plan-format:\" WS? Int WS? \"-->\" NL\n335\tPreamble    ← H1 NL Prose?\n336\tPhaseOrBugs ← Phase / BugsSection\n337\tPhase       ← PhaseHead PhaseIdComment? Prose? Subsection* Item+\n338\tPhaseHead   ← \"##\" WS (\"Stage\" / \"Phase\") WS Int \":\" WS Text NL\n339\tPhaseIdComment ← \"<!--\" WS? \"phase_id:\" WS? Word WS? \"-->\" NL\n340\tSubsection  ← \"###\" WS Text NL Prose?\n341\tBugsSection ← \"##\" WS \"Bugs\" NL Item*\n342\tItem        ← Indent* \"-\" WS \"[\" Status \"]\" WS TaskId Tag* Text Annot* NL DepsLine? Item* RuledOut*\n343\tStatus      ← \" \" / \"x\" / \"X\" / \"!\"\n344\tTaskId      ← TaskRef \":\" WS                      ; the colon-suffixed form used as a task's own ID\n345\tTaskRef     ← \"T-\" Digit+                         ; the bare form used to reference another task\n346\tTag         ← FlagTag / ActionTag                 ; leading position only (§4.3)\n347\tFlagTag     ← \"[\" (\"USER\" / \"BATCH\") \"]\" WS\n348\tActionTag   ← \"[AUTO:\" Word \"]\" WS Text?          ; args are remainder of text\n349\tAnnot       ← WS \"[\" Key \":\" WS Value \"]\"         ; e.g. [feat: \"...\"], [fix: \"...\"]\n350\tDepsLine    ← Indent* \"@deps\" (WS TaskRef)+ NL    ; bare IDs, no trailing colon\n351\tRuledOut    ← Indent* \"[RULEDOUT]\" WS Text NL\n352\tIndent      ← (WS WS)+                            ; numeric nesting, 2-space canonical\n353\tProse       ← (! Item ! PhaseHead ! Subsection . )* NL\n354\t```\n355\t\n356\tNotes on the grammar:\n357\t\n358\t- Indentation is significant for nesting but **numeric**, not fixed.\n359\t  A child task requires strictly greater indent than its parent.\n360\t  The canonical renderer emits two-space units; the parser accepts\n361\t  any consistent unit ≥ 1 space. (Duplo's PLAN.md uses 2; McLoop's\n362\t  uses 3; PLAN.EXAMPLE.md uses 2.)\n363\t- Unknown bracket tags are rejected by validation, not silently\n364\t  ignored. New tags require a library change.\n365\t- Prose is allowed in three places: preamble after H1, phase prose\n366\t  after a phase heading, and subsection prose after a `###`\n367\t  heading. Loose checklist items inside Prose are syntax errors.\n368\t- The `<!-- bob-plan-format: 1 -->` magic line is recommended but\n369\t  optional during migration; its absence triggers compatibility\n370\t  mode (see §8).\n371\t\n372\t### 4.3 Tag families\n373\t\n374\tThree families. Position rules are stricter than McLoop's current\n375\tsubstring-matching behavior: operational tags are recognized **only\n376\tin the leading position** of a task line, immediately after the\n377\tcheckbox and task ID. This is a deliberate departure from McLoop,\n378\twhich classifies any task whose text contains `[USER]` anywhere as\n379\ta USER task. A task description that references the tag form in\n380\tprose (in quoted code, in example text, in references to the syntax\n381\titself) is not classified as that operational kind.\n382\t\n383\t1. **Flag tags** (`[USER]`, `[BATCH]`): must appear immediately\n384\t   after the checkbox and task ID, before the task description.\n385\t   `[USER]` or `[BATCH]` appearing later in the text is prose, not\n386\t   a tag.\n387\t2. **Action tags** (`[AUTO:<action>] <args>`): must appear\n388\t   immediately after the flag tags (if any) and before the task\n389\t   description. The argument string is the text from the closing\n390\t   bracket of the action tag to end of line. `[AUTO:...]` tokens\n391\t   appearing later in the text are prose.\n392\t3. **Key-value annotations** (`[feat: \"...\"]`, `[fix: \"...\"]`): at\n393\t   end of line. Multiple allowed.\n394\t\n395\tCompatibility mode parses leading tags as tags and treats non-leading\n396\tbracketed tokens that resemble flag or action tags as prose. The\n397\tparser may emit a validation warning when a non-leading token like\n398\t`[USER]` appears inside task text — the warning is opt-in; the\n399\tdefault is silent acceptance as prose.\n400\t\n401\tThe `migrate` operation does **not** auto-promote non-leading\n402\tbracketed tokens into operational tags. Migrating a plan whose task\n403\tdescription mentions `[USER]` in prose leaves the bracket form as\n404\ttext; it does not silently convert the task into a USER task.\n405\t\n406\t`[RULEDOUT]` is **not** a task tag. It is a sibling line at the\n407\tchild indent under the task it pertains to, matching McLoop's\n408\texisting convention. Reserved for the indent-attached rule.\n409\t\n410\t## 5. Status model and settlement contract\n411\t\n412\tPLAN.md keeps the three-valued checkbox. The ledger keeps the rich\n413\tstatus enum and task-outcome evidence. These surfaces are related,\n414\tbut they are not currently a strict bidirectional invariant.\n415\t\n416\tCurrent behavior:\n417\t\n418\t- Standard code-edit success checks off the task in PLAN.md, then\n419\t  calls `_ledger_settle(..., TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))`\n420\t  (`main.py`, lines 1673-1712). `ledger_emit` emits\n421\t  `commit_landed` only if a git HEAD sha exists (lines 382-425 and\n422\t  subsequent success branch).\n423\t- Standard retry exhaustion marks the task `[!]`, then calls\n424\t  `_ledger_settle(..., TaskOutcome(success=False, abandoned=True,\n425\t  failure_kind=\"max_retries_exceeded\"))` (`main.py`, lines\n426\t  1761-1778).\n427\t- Commit failure calls `_ledger_settle(..., failure_kind=\"commit_failed\")`\n428\t  but does not currently mark the checkbox `[!]` before the terminal\n429\t  failure break (`main.py`, lines 1652-1664). This is a current\n430\t  inconsistency, not a planfile design rule.\n431\t- `[AUTO]` and successful `[USER]` tasks are checked off directly and\n432\t  do **not** currently call `_ledger_settle` (`main.py`, lines\n433\t  1181-1216).\n434\t- Parent auto-checking can mark parent tasks `[x]` as a derived\n435\t  operation without emitting a separate ledger event\n436\t  (`checklist.py`, lines 730-756).\n437\t\n438\tTarget contract after McLoop migrates to planfile:\n439\t\n440\t```\n441\tEvery planfile-mediated task settlement returns:\n442\t  - the new Plan text state\n443\t  - a Settlement describing what ledger event, if any, the caller\n444\t    should emit\n445\t  - whether the checkbox state is direct or derived\n446\t```\n447\t\n448\tThe intended mapping is:\n449\t\n450\t- Direct success with a commit -> `[x]` plus `commit_landed`.\n451\t- Direct success without a commit, including `[AUTO]` / `[USER]`\n452\t  verification -> `[x]` plus `work_observed`. This uses an existing\n453\t  ledger event type and keeps human/automatic verification visible\n454\t  without inventing a task-specific schema before the ledger is ready\n455\t  for `attributed_task_id`.\n456\t- Direct terminal task failure -> `[!]` plus `test_failed`.\n457\t- Derived parent completion -> `[x]` with\n458\t  `ledger_event_required=False`.\n459\t- Resetting `[!]` to `[ ]` via retry -> no ledger event; it is an\n460\t  operator decision to retry existing work, not evidence about the\n461\t  implementation.\n462\t- No outcome yet -> `[ ]`.\n463\t\n464\tThe library exposes a checker for this target contract:\n465\t\n466\t```\n467\tcheck_consistency(plan: Plan, events: list[Event]) -> None | PlanInconsistencyError\n468\t```\n469\t\n470\tThe checker must understand the exceptions above. It should flag\n471\tonly contradictions, not intentional ledger gaps such as derived\n472\tparent completion or explicit no-ledger settlements.\n473\t\n474\tThe directionality stays as it is in the code today: PLAN.md is\n475\twritten first, the ledger event is emitted as evidence. The library's\n476\tmutation operations (`complete_task`, `fail_task`, `reset_task`)\n477\treturn both the new `Plan` and a tuple of settlement descriptors:\n478\t\n479\t```python\n480\tnew_plan, settlements = complete_task(plan, \"T-000001\",\n481\t    outcome=TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))\n482\tsave(path, new_plan)\n483\tfor settlement in settlements:\n484\t    if not settlement.ledger_event_required:\n485\t        continue\n486\t    storage.append(build_ledger_event(settlement))\n487\t```\n488\t\n489\tThe caller maps each `Settlement` into a concrete ledger event\n490\t(e.g. `commit_landed`, `work_observed`, `test_failed`) before\n491\tappending. The `Settlement` itself carries only the descriptor\n492\tfields listed above (kind, task_id, phase_id, summary,\n493\tfailure_kind, ledger_event_required); construction of the\n494\twire-format event is the caller's responsibility, because event\n495\tpayloads need run-context (run_id, writer_id, transcript_ref) that\n496\tthe planfile library does not own.\n497\t\n498\tThe tuple form makes derived parent completion explicit: completing\n499\ta leaf that also auto-checks its parent returns two settlements\n500\t(the leaf's `commit_landed` or `work_observed`, then the parent's\n501\t`kind=\"none\"` derived settlement). Callers iterate the tuple and\n502\temit only the settlements whose `ledger_event_required` is true.\n503\tFor leaf tasks with no derived effects the tuple has one element.\n504\t\n505\tThe two writes stay coupled at the call site, not at the library\n506\tboundary. This matches the existing `_ledger_settle` flow rather\n507\tthan fighting it.\n508\t\n509\t## 6. Semantics: `next_tasks`\n510\t\n511\tThe algorithm preserves McLoop's `find_next` behavior. A task is\n512\tactionable iff:\n513\t\n514\t1. Status is `[ ]`.\n515\t2. Every task ID listed in the task's `@deps` line (per §4.2) is\n516\t   complete (`[x]`). Dependencies that do not resolve to a known\n517\t   task are validation errors (raised by `validate_plan`), not\n518\t   actionability blockers; `next_tasks` does not raise on unknown\n519\t   refs. **Contract**: `next_tasks` assumes a validated Plan.\n520\t   Callers must run `validate_plan` before scheduling. CLI\n521\t   subcommands that schedule (`bob-plan next`, `bob-plan done`,\n522\t   `bob-plan fail`) call `validate_plan` internally before\n523\t   dispatching to `next_tasks` or mutation operations; library\n524\t   callers that bypass the CLI must do the same.\n525\t3. No failed (`[!]`) ancestor exists.\n526\t4. If the task has children, return the first actionable child\n527\t   before the parent.\n528\t\n529\tPriority and scoping:\n530\t\n531\t1. Tasks under `## Bugs` have absolute priority over phase tasks.\n532\t2. Within phase tasks, only tasks in the **first incomplete phase**\n533\t   (document order) are returned. Later phases are invisible until\n534\t   the current phase is fully `[x]`.\n535\t3. Failed subtasks block later siblings under the same parent\n536\t   (implicit sequential dependency).\n537\t4. A failed child prevents parent completion. Parent completion is\n538\t   **derived** from children (no independent parent state).\n539\t\n540\tOutput:\n541\t\n542\t```\n543\tnext_tasks(plan, limit=1) -> list[Task]\n544\t```\n545\t\n546\tA `[USER]` task surfaces as \"halt and surface to human\"; a\n547\t`[BATCH]` parent surfaces as one unit (its actionable children\n548\tjoined); an `[AUTO:<action>]` task surfaces with its action and\n549\targs.\n550\t\n551\t## 7. Phase and task identity\n552\t\n553\t### 7.1 Phase identity\n554\t\n555\tThree mechanisms, in resolution order:\n556\t\n557\t1. `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->` comment immediately after the\n558\t   phase heading. **Canonical form** going forward. Already\n559\t   recognized by `ledger_emit.find_explicit_phase_id_for_task`.\n560\t2. Legacy `## Phase phase_NNN: Title` heading. Recognized by the\n561\t   ledger today, but **breaks McLoop's STAGE_RE**. Accepted by the\n562\t   parser for read-only migration purposes; the canonicalizer\n563\t   rewrites to form 1.\n564\t3. Ordinal fallback. The n-th phase heading in document order. Emits\n565\t   a `finding_observed` event tagged `degraded` (current behavior,\n566\t   preserved).\n567\t\n568\t`planfile.resolve_task_context(plan, task_label)` becomes the single\n569\tresolver. `ledger_emit.resolve_phase_id` becomes a thin shim:\n570\t\n571\t```python\n572\tdef resolve_phase_id(*, plan_path, task_label, ordinal_index=None):\n573\t    plan = planfile.load(plan_path)\n574\t    ctx = planfile.resolve_task_context(plan, task_label)\n575\t    if ctx.phase_id_source == \"explicit\":\n576\t        return PhaseIdResolution(ctx.phase_id, \"explicit\", ctx.plan_phase_count)\n577\t    if ordinal_index is not None and ...:\n578\t        return PhaseIdResolution(..., \"ordinal\", ...)\n579\t    return PhaseIdResolution(None, \"none\", ctx.plan_phase_count)\n580\t```\n581\t\n582\t### 7.2 Task identity\n583\t\n584\t`T-NNNNNN:` IDs are mandatory in the canonical form, optional in\n585\tthe compatibility-mode parser. Migration assigns IDs once on first\n586\tparse and writes them back. After migration, tasks are referenced\n587\tby ID, not by text or label.\n588\t\n589\t**Caveat about ledger attribution today**: the\n590\t`commit_landed` event has `attributed_phase_id` but no `task_id`\n591\tfield. Task identity flows through `test_failed.test_id` (which is\n592\tthe task label, per `emit_task_lifecycle_events`). Adding stable\n593\ttask IDs to PLAN.md does not by itself make commits attribute to\n594\ttasks. Two paths forward:\n595\t\n596\t- **Short-term**: McLoop's settle hook maps `task_label → task_id`\n597\t  via `planfile.resolve_task_context`. The ID appears in\n598\t  `test_failed.test_id` instead of the label. `commit_landed`\n599\t  continues to attribute to phase only.\n600\t- **Longer-term**: ledger schema adds `attributed_task_id` to\n601\t  `commit_landed`. Requires a schema version bump; not part of\n602\t  this proposal.\n603\t\n604\t**Caveat about substring matching**:\n605\t`find_explicit_phase_id_for_task` currently uses\n606\t`label_token in line` — pure substring match. This is brittle\n607\ttoday and breaks once `T-NNNNNN:` lands\n608\t(`T-000001` is a substring of `T-0000010`). The library must\n609\ttokenize and match against parsed task entries, not raw line\n610\tsubstrings. Pin in the contract.\n611\t\n612\t## 8. Migration\n613\t\n614\tPhased migration. No big-bang rewrite.\n615\t\n616\t### Phase A: parser-only\n617\t\n618\t1. Add `bob_tools.planfile` with the parser, renderer, validator,\n619\t   and migrator. Parser accepts both old (no IDs, headings without\n620\t   phase-id comments) and new (with IDs and comments) forms.\n621\t   Renderer emits canonical form. `migrate(plan)` is a separate\n622\t   operation that assigns missing IDs and phase-id comments.\n623\t2. `@deps` is supported from the start. The parser reads `@deps`\n624\t   lines, the renderer writes them, validation requires referenced\n625\t   IDs to exist in the plan, and `next_tasks` honors deps when\n626\t   deciding actionability. Minimal scope: dependency graph cycle\n627\t   detection is *not* required in Phase A (a cycle just blocks\n628\t   `next_tasks` from progressing past it; callers detect that as\n629\t   no actionable task remaining).\n630\t3. Add `bob-plan validate PLAN.md` and `bob-plan fmt PLAN.md`\n631\t   commands. `fmt` calls `parse_plan`, then `migrate`, then\n632\t   `save`. Idempotent.\n633\t4. McLoop and Duplo continue to use their existing parsers during\n634\t   Phase A.\n635\t\n636\t### Phase B: McLoop migration\n637\t\n638\t1. McLoop's settle hook calls `planfile.resolve_task_context`\n639\t   instead of `ledger_emit.find_explicit_phase_id_for_task`.\n640\t   `resolve_phase_id` becomes a shim.\n641\t2. `mcloop.checklist.parse` delegates to `planfile.parse_plan`.\n642\t   `check_off`, `mark_failed`, `find_next` delegate to\n643\t   `planfile.complete_task`, `fail_task`, `next_tasks`.\n644\t3. McLoop's parser disappears or remains as a 5-line shim.\n645\t\n646\t### Phase C: Duplo migration\n647\t\n648\t1. Duplo's planner stops emitting raw Markdown. It produces typed\n649\t   `Plan` objects (via LLM-proposed task text, but with structure\n650\t   assigned by Duplo). Duplo calls `planfile.render_plan` to write.\n651\t2. LLM output is validated by `planfile.validate_plan` before\n652\t   write. Malformed output is rejected; Duplo retries or fails the\n653\t   phase. The LLM never owns plan structure.\n654\t3. Duplo annotations (`[feat: \"...\"]`, `[fix: \"...\"]`) are\n655\t   first-class in the typed `Plan` (fields on `Task`), not parsed\n656\t   from text.\n657\t\n658\t### Phase D: cleanup\n659\t\n660\t1. Delete `mcloop.checklist` if the shim has no remaining callers.\n661\t2. Decide whether `commit_landed` should gain `attributed_task_id`.\n662\t   If yes, that is a ledger schema bump, not a planfile change.\n663\t\n664\t## 9. What changes for humans\n665\t\n666\tHumans can still hand-edit PLAN.md. Constraints:\n667\t\n668\t- Editing task text is safe.\n669\t- Editing checkboxes is safe; the consistency check will surface\n670\t  divergence from the ledger on the next run, but does not auto-\n671\t  rewrite.\n672\t- **Do not** edit `T-NNNNNN:` IDs or remove `<!-- phase_id: -->`\n673\t  comments. Either is detected and rejected with a line-located\n674\t  error.\n675\t- `bob-plan fmt PLAN.md` is safe to run anytime: it normalizes\n676\t  whitespace, sorts annotations into canonical position, and\n677\t  assigns IDs to any new tasks. Idempotent.\n678\t\n679\tWhen McLoop refuses to run, the message is:\n680\t\n681\t```\n682\tPLAN.md invalid at line 17, column 5:\n683\texpected task id like T-000123 after checkbox marker\n684\t```\n685\t\n686\tNo best-effort recovery. The user runs `bob-plan validate` to see\n687\tall errors, fixes them by hand, or runs `bob-plan fmt` for\n688\tstructural normalization.\n689\t\n690\t## 10. Out of scope\n691\t\n692\t- `commit_landed.attributed_task_id`. Mentioned in §7.2 as a\n693\t  future-work item; not part of this proposal.\n694\t- Replacing the Plan Ledger. The ledger is the audit/event surface;\n695\t  planfile is the syntax surface. They coexist.\n696\t- A \"running\" status in PLAN.md. McLoop tracks live state in\n697\t  `.mcloop/runs/latest.json` and a lock file; a crashed run should\n698\t  not leave the plan in a \"claimed\" state.\n699\t- Multi-writer locking semantics for PLAN.md beyond file locking\n700\t  and atomic writes. Concurrent human + tool edits during a run\n701\t  are out of scope; McLoop already prints\n702\t  `\"Do not edit CURRENT_PLAN.md or BUGS.md while mcloop is running\"`\n703\t  on startup.\n704\t\n705\t## 11. Open questions\n706\t\n707\t1. **Should `T-NNNNNN:` be globally unique or per-phase?** Globally\n708\t   unique is simpler for ledger attribution; per-phase makes IDs\n709\t   smaller and locally meaningful. Global preferred unless there's a\n710\t   reason against.\n711\t\n712\t2. **What is the migration story for the four existing PLAN.md\n713\t   files?** (Duplo, McLoop, McLoop's PLAN.EXAMPLE, and any in target\n714\t   projects.) `bob-plan fmt` should handle all four. Verify\n715\t   round-trip on each before claiming Phase A complete.\n716\t\n717\t3. **Should `[RULEDOUT]` move from sibling-line to a field on `Task`?**\n718\t   The runtime behavior is identical (collected and fed to the\n719\t   prompt); the only difference is whether it appears as\n720\t   indent-attached prose or as a structured field. The current sibling-\n721\t   line form survives canonicalization unchanged; the structured form\n722\t   would require a schema decision. Recommendation: keep sibling-line\n723\t   form; treat `[RULEDOUT]` as a parser-collected per-task list in the\n724\t   `Task` object. No syntax change.\n725\t\n726\t4. **How are `## Stage` and `## Phase` headings reconciled?** Both\n727\t   work today and mean the same thing. Recommendation: parser\n728\t   accepts both; canonicalizer leaves them as-is (does not rewrite\n729\t   \"Stage\" to \"Phase\" or vice versa). The keyword is cosmetic; the\n730\t   `phase_id` carries identity.\n731\t\n732\t5. **What about subsection headings (`### Manual verification`)?**\n733\t   Currently used in Duplo's PLAN.md to group tasks within a phase.\n734\t   The parser must accept them. They have no semantic effect on\n735\t   `next_tasks` or `phase_id`. Recommendation: parse as structural,\n736\t   preserve through round-trip, attach contained tasks to the parent\n737\t   phase's `phase_id`.\n738\t\n739\t6. **Is the settlement consistency check per-run or all-time?** The\n740\t   target contract in §5 should start per-run. All-time enforcement\n741\t   would require the ledger to be the source of truth across runs,\n742\t   which contradicts the directionality decision. Recommendation:\n743\t   per-run. Cross-run consistency is an audit command, not\n744\t   `bob-plan validate`'s default behavior.\n745\t\n746\t7. **What happens when a `[USER]` task is checked off without a user\n747\t   prompt?** Today nothing checks; a hand-edit can flip\n748\t   `- [ ] [USER] Verify the menu appears` to `- [x] [USER] Verify the\n749\t   menu appears` and McLoop accepts it. Recommendation: keep the\n750\t   current permissive behavior during compatibility mode. After\n751\t   planfile-mediated settlement lands, McLoop-created `[USER]`\n752\t   completions should emit `work_observed`; hand-edited `[x]` user\n753\t   tasks remain accepted as explicit human assertions and are not\n754\t   rejected merely because no ledger event exists.\n755\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac94cef0-99df-4cb6-aede-46072f55262c","uuid":"3f2ba33b-0e1b-45b3-931a-322f6478e01a","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:41:30.567Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/mhcoen/proj/bob/design/planfile.md","content":"# `bob_tools.planfile`: deterministic PLAN.md handling\n\nStatus: draft for discussion. Scope: define a single library that owns\nPLAN.md syntax, parsing, serialization, and operations across McLoop,\nDuplo, and human editors, so that PLAN.md handling stops being\nLLM-mediated and starts being deterministic.\n\nThis document is structured for cold review. Every claim about\nexisting behavior cites the file and function it was verified against.\nEvery proposed addition is marked as such. Open questions are flagged\nexplicitly at the end.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Problem\n\nPLAN.md is currently produced, parsed, and mutated by three actors:\nMcLoop's runner, Duplo's planner, and humans editing directly.\nMcLoop has a real parser\n(`mcloop/checklist.py:parse`, line 151); Duplo writes through an\nLLM and a partial postprocess; humans edit freely. The three actors\ndo not share a single contract, and the LLM-mediated paths have\nproduced corruption that McLoop's parser explicitly refuses to\nauto-fix (`PlanCorruptionError`, `mcloop/checklist.py:27`; the\nfail-closed message is assembled at lines 142-148).\n\nThe goal is to make PLAN.md handling deterministic without removing\nthe human-editable property. Concretely:\n\n- One library owns parsing, serialization, validation, and operations.\n- McLoop and Duplo call the library; the LLM never owns plan structure.\n- Humans may still hand-edit, but tools refuse to \"best-effort\" parse\n  malformed input. Errors are line/column-located.\n- The library coexists with the Plan Ledger\n  (`bob_tools/ledger/`); it is not a replacement for the audit/event\n  surface that already exists.\n\n## 2. Current state (audit)\n\nThis section records what is already on disk, with citations, so the\ndesign does not invent state that already exists or contradict\nbehavior that the runner depends on.\n\n### 2.1 McLoop's parser\n\n`mcloop/checklist.py` is the working parser. It defines:\n\n- `CHECKBOX_RE = r\"^(\\s*)- \\[([ xX!])\\] (.+)$\"` (line 9). Four markers\n  are admitted: space (todo), `x`/`X` (done), `!` (failed).\n- `STAGE_RE = r\"^#+\\s+.*?\\b(?:stage|phase)\\s+(\\d+)\\b\"` (line 12). Any\n  heading level whose title contains `Stage N` or `Phase N` is a\n  section header. The `\\d+` is mandatory — bare digits only.\n- `BUGS_RE = r\"^#+\\s+Bugs\\s*$\"` (line 14). Any heading level titled\n  exactly `Bugs` is the bug-priority section.\n- Four operational tags: `[USER]` (`_USER_TAG`, line 22),\n  `[BATCH]` (`_BATCH_TAG`, line 23), `[AUTO:<action>]`\n  (`_AUTO_TAG_RE`, line 24), and `[RULEDOUT]` as a non-task\n  indent-attached line (handled in `parse`, lines 189-204).\n- `PlanCorruptionError` (line 27) is raised on duplicate H1 titles,\n  multiple `## Bugs` sections, or duplicate phase/stage numbers.\n  Auto-fixing is deliberately not attempted (the docstring at line\n  26 records the rationale).\n\nThe status enum is **three-valued**: `[ ] / [x] / [!]`. The `[USER]`\ntoken is an orthogonal in-text tag, not a checkbox state.\n`is_user_task` (line 627) substring-searches the task text.\n\n### 2.2 McLoop's execution semantics\n\n`mcloop/main.py:run_loop` consumes the parsed tree and dispatches on\nthe tags:\n\n- `[AUTO:<action>]` tasks call `_handle_auto_task(label, action, args)`\n  and are checked off automatically. The action vocabulary\n  (`run_cli`, `run_gui`, `screenshot`, etc.) is interpreted by\n  `mcloop/investigate_cmd.py`.\n- `[USER]` tasks pause the run, print formatted instructions, and\n  accept free-form text input. A failed `[USER]` verification files\n  a new bug into BUGS.md and sets `terminal_failure`; the `[USER]`\n  task itself stays unchecked for re-verification after the bug is\n  fixed.\n- `[BATCH]` parents collect consecutive unchecked children via\n  `get_batch_children` (line 654) and run them as a single\n  session. `[USER]` or `[AUTO:…]` children halt batch collection.\n- `[RULEDOUT]` lines feed `get_eliminated(tasks, task)` whose result\n  is appended to the task prompt as a \"RULED OUT APPROACHES\" block,\n  suppressing repeat strategies (verified in\n  `mcloop/runner.py`, lines 376-385, 422-431, and 482-491).\n\n`find_next` (line 434) implements the actionable-task algorithm:\n\n1. Bug tasks (under `## Bugs`) have absolute priority.\n2. Otherwise, only tasks in the first incomplete stage are returned.\n3. Failed subtasks (`[!]`) block all later siblings under the same\n   parent (implicit sequential dependency,\n   `_search_tasks`, lines 369-376).\n4. A failed child prevents parent completion\n   (`_auto_check_parents`, lines 730-756).\n5. Auto-check parent when all children are done.\n\n`clear_failed_markers` (line 593) resets `[!]` back to `[ ]` on\n`--retry`, anchored to checkbox syntax so prose containing the\nliteral `- [!]` is not corrupted (lines 607-610).\n\n### 2.3 The Plan Ledger\n\n`bob_tools/ledger/` is already shipped and integrated into McLoop:\n\n- `bob_tools/ledger/SCHEMA.md` defines the on-disk format\n  (`PLAN.events.jsonl`, append-only, one JSON object per line,\n  envelope with `event_id` UUIDv7, `seq`, `writer_id`, `run_id`,\n  `payload`).\n- `mcloop/main.py` imports from `mcloop.ledger_config`,\n  `mcloop.ledger_emit`, `mcloop.ledger_pause` and calls\n  `_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(...))` after every task in\n  the standard code-edit success/failure path. Exit code 5 is\n  reserved for ledger-induced hard stops (`HardStop`, `main.py`,\n  lines 218-244).\n- `mcloop/ledger_config.py` gates the ledger with, in precedence\n  order, CLI flags, `MCLOOP_NO_PLAN_LEDGER` /\n  `MCLOOP_NO_AUTO_REAUTHOR`, `.orchestra/config.json`, and finally\n  auto-detection of `<project>/.duplo/ledger/` (lines 1-17 and\n  70-142).\n- `mcloop/ledger_pause.py` evaluates thresholds after settlement and\n  either returns no pause, invokes Duplo reauthor, or raises\n  `HardStop`. It is explicitly fail-closed: failed reauthor leaves\n  PLAN.md unchanged and records only the triggering crossing on the\n  ledger (lines 1-22 and 297-420). Planfile does not need a separate\n  \"paused state\" check; the settle/evaluate path already owns that\n  decision.\n- The ledger's status model is **richer than the parser's**:\n  `pending | active | completed | abandoned | superseded | split |\n  merged | blocked | provisional` (SCHEMA.md \"Phase status enum\").\n- `TaskOutcome` (in `mcloop/ledger_emit.py:TaskOutcome`) carries\n  `success`, `abandoned`, `summary`, `changed_files`,\n  `failure_kind`, `transcript_ref`. The `failure_kind` field\n  records `\"commit_failed\"`, `\"max_retries_exceeded\"`, etc.\n\n### 2.4 Phase identity in the ledger today\n\n`mcloop/ledger_emit.py` resolves phase IDs from PLAN.md via two\nregexes:\n\n```python\n_PHASE_HEADER_RE = re.compile(\n    r\"^##\\s+Phase\\s+(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+):\\s+(?P<title>.+?)\\s*$\"\n)\n_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE = re.compile(\n    r\"<!--\\s*phase_id\\s*:\\s*(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+)\\s*-->\"\n)\n```\n\n`find_explicit_phase_id_for_task(plan_text, task_label)` iterates\nline by line. A line matching `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` sets\n`current_phase_id`. A line containing the `task_label` as a\nsubstring returns the current `current_phase_id`. A line matching\n`_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE` updates `current_phase_id` for subsequent\ntasks.\n\n`resolve_phase_id(plan_path, task_label, ordinal_index)` implements\nthe explicit-required / ordinal-degraded contract. When the\nexplicit lookup yields nothing, `ordinal_index` maps to the n-th\nphase header found. When that path runs, `record_phase_id_fallback`\nprints a stderr warning and emits a `finding_observed` event tagged\n`degraded`.\n\n### 2.5 The format incompatibility\n\nMcLoop's `STAGE_RE` requires `\\bphase\\s+\\d+\\b` — bare digits after\n\"phase\". The ledger's `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` accepts\n`[A-Za-z0-9_]+` after \"Phase\". The following table shows what each\nheading produces:\n\n| Heading                                            | McLoop STAGE_RE     | Ledger header regex             |\n|----------------------------------------------------|---------------------|---------------------------------|\n| `## Phase 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | matches, `phase_id=\"1\"`         |\n| `## Phase phase_001: Core`                         | **does not match**  | matches, `phase_id=\"phase_001\"` |\n| `## Stage 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | does not match                  |\n| `## Stage 1: Core` + `<!-- phase_id: phase_001 -->`| matches (stage 1)   | matches via comment             |\n\nOnly the dual-line form satisfies both regexes today **and**\ndelivers a stable string phase_id distinct from the ordinal. The\nsingle-heading `## Phase phase_001:` form breaks McLoop's stage\ndetection.\n\nA second-order consequence: a hypothetical `## Phase 1: ...` heading\nwould match both regexes, but the ledger would derive\n`phase_id=\"1\"` from it. The current Duplo PLAN.md uses H1 phase\nheadings (`# Phase 1: ...`), which McLoop's `STAGE_RE` accepts but\nthe ledger header regex does not. In both cases, the stable-ID\nmigration cost is one `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->` line per phase,\nwith no rewrite of the visible heading.\n\n### 2.6 PLAN.md / ledger directionality\n\n`run_loop`'s success path calls `check_off(active_file, task)` to\nwrite `[x]` to PLAN.md *first*, then calls\n`_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))` which emits\na `commit_landed` event as audit evidence of what PLAN.md already\nrecords. PLAN.md is the writable surface; the ledger is the\nappend-only witness. Hand-edits flow PLAN.md → ledger, never the\nreverse.\n\n## 3. Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Library placement\n\n```\nbob/\n  bob_tools/\n    ledger/       # already exists; owns events + projected state\n    planfile/     # NEW; owns PLAN.md syntax + canonicalization\n      model.py\n      parser.py\n      renderer.py\n      operations.py\n      fileio.py\n      cli.py\n      tests/\n```\n\nThe two libraries are peers. They cross at exactly two values:\n\n- `phase_id`: written and read by `planfile` via headings and\n  `<!-- phase_id: ... -->` comments; consumed by `ledger` in event\n  payloads.\n- `task_label`: computed by `planfile` from position and stable IDs;\n  resolved to `phase_id` (and, when stable task IDs land, to\n  `task_id`) by the McLoop settle hook.\n\n`mcloop.checklist` becomes a thin compatibility wrapper or\ndisappears once callers migrate. `mcloop.plan_split` and Duplo's\nplanner write through `planfile`.\n\n### 3.2 Function inventory (proposed)\n\nPure operations on typed objects:\n\n```\nparse_plan(text)               -> Plan | PlanSyntaxError\nrender_plan(plan)              -> str\nvalidate_plan(plan)            -> None | PlanValidationError\ncanonicalize(text)             -> str\nmigrate(plan)                  -> Plan\nnext_tasks(plan, limit=1)      -> list[Task]\ncomplete_task(plan, task_id, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\nfail_task(plan, task_id, reason, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\nreset_task(plan, task_id)      -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\nadd_task(plan, phase_id, text, deps=(), parent_id=None) -> Plan\nreplace_phase(plan, phase_id, new_phase) -> Plan\nresolve_task_context(plan, task_label_or_id) -> {phase_id, task_id, label}\ncheck_consistency(plan, events) -> None | PlanInconsistencyError\n```\n\nFile operations wrap those with locking and atomic writes:\n\n```\nload(path) -> Plan\nsave(path, plan) -> None\nupdate(path, operation) -> Plan\n```\n\nImplementation rule: only `parse_plan` and `render_plan` touch text.\nEverything else operates on typed objects.\n\nThe split between `canonicalize` and `migrate`:\n\n- `canonicalize(text)` is lossless formatting: parse the input,\n  re-render in canonical form. Does **not** assign IDs or add\n  phase-id comments. Input that already has IDs round-trips through\n  `canonicalize` unchanged; input without IDs is rendered without\n  IDs (compatibility output).\n- `migrate(plan) -> Plan` mutates identity: assigns `T-NNNNNN:` IDs\n  to tasks that have none, adds `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->`\n  comments to phases that have none. Otherwise leaves the plan\n  unchanged. Identity assignment is not formatting and must be\n  explicit, not folded into a \"format\" operation.\n- `bob-plan fmt PATH` is the composition: parse, migrate, save.\n  ```python\n  plan = parse_plan(text)\n  plan = migrate(plan)\n  save(path, plan)\n  ```\n\nMutation operations return a tuple of Settlements rather than a\nsingle one. A direct completion that also auto-checks a parent\nreturns `(direct_settlement, derived_no_event_settlement)` — explicit\nand testable. Callers do not infer derived state by diffing Plans.\nFor tasks with no derived effects the tuple has one element.\n\n## 4. Canonical syntax\n\nThe grammar is a strict subset of GFM Markdown. McLoop's existing\nsyntax is the floor; the only **additions** are stable IDs and the\noptional `<!-- phase_id: -->` comment (which the ledger already\nrecognizes).\n\n### 4.1 Example\n\n```markdown\n<!-- bob-plan-format: 1 -->\n\n# Project Name\n\nProject prose is allowed here, before the first phase heading.\n\n## Stage 1: Core\n<!-- phase_id: phase_001 -->\n\nPhase prose is allowed here, before the first task.\n\n- [ ] T-000001: [BATCH] Markdown checklist parser\n  - [ ] T-000002: Parse tasks from markdown checkboxes\n  - [ ] T-000003: Find the next unchecked item\n    [RULEDOUT] Do not identify tasks by text alone; duplicate text is legal.\n  - [x] T-000004: Check off completed items in the file\n- [ ] T-000005: [USER] Launch the app and confirm the main window appears\n- [ ] T-000006: [AUTO:run_cli] mcloop --dry-run\n- [!] T-000007: Fix failing import path\n\n### Manual verification\n\n- [ ] T-000008: Run the smoke test by hand\n\n## Bugs\n\n- [ ] T-000009: Crash on empty PLAN.md\n```\n\n### 4.2 Productions\n\n```\nPlan        ← Magic Preamble? PhaseOrBugs+ EOF\nMagic       ← \"<!--\" WS? \"bob-plan-format:\" WS? Int WS? \"-->\" NL\nPreamble    ← H1 NL Prose?\nPhaseOrBugs ← Phase / BugsSection\nPhase       ← PhaseHead PhaseIdComment? Prose? Subsection* Item+\nPhaseHead   ← \"##\" WS (\"Stage\" / \"Phase\") WS Int \":\" WS Text NL\nPhaseIdComment ← \"<!--\" WS? \"phase_id:\" WS? Word WS? \"-->\" NL\nSubsection  ← \"###\" WS Text NL Prose?\nBugsSection ← \"##\" WS \"Bugs\" NL Item*\nItem        ← Indent* \"-\" WS \"[\" Status \"]\" WS TaskId Tag* Text Annot* NL DepsLine? Item* RuledOut*\nStatus      ← \" \" / \"x\" / \"X\" / \"!\"\nTaskId      ← TaskRef \":\" WS                      ; the colon-suffixed form used as a task's own ID\nTaskRef     ← \"T-\" Digit+                         ; the bare form used to reference another task\nTag         ← FlagTag / ActionTag                 ; leading position only (§4.3)\nFlagTag     ← \"[\" (\"USER\" / \"BATCH\") \"]\" WS\nActionTag   ← \"[AUTO:\" Word \"]\" WS Text?          ; args are remainder of text\nAnnot       ← WS \"[\" Key \":\" WS Value \"]\"         ; e.g. [feat: \"...\"], [fix: \"...\"]\nDepsLine    ← Indent* \"@deps\" (WS TaskRef)+ NL    ; bare IDs, no trailing colon\nRuledOut    ← Indent* \"[RULEDOUT]\" WS Text NL\nIndent      ← (WS WS)+                            ; numeric nesting, 2-space canonical\nProse       ← (! Item ! PhaseHead ! Subsection . )* NL\n```\n\nNotes on the grammar:\n\n- Indentation is significant for nesting but **numeric**, not fixed.\n  A child task requires strictly greater indent than its parent.\n  The canonical renderer emits two-space units; the parser accepts\n  any consistent unit ≥ 1 space. (Duplo's PLAN.md uses 2; McLoop's\n  uses 3; PLAN.EXAMPLE.md uses 2.)\n- Unknown bracket tags are rejected by validation, not silently\n  ignored. New tags require a library change.\n- Prose is allowed in three places: preamble after H1, phase prose\n  after a phase heading, and subsection prose after a `###`\n  heading. Loose checklist items inside Prose are syntax errors.\n- The `<!-- bob-plan-format: 1 -->` magic line is recommended but\n  optional during migration; its absence triggers compatibility\n  mode (see §8).\n\n### 4.3 Tag families\n\nThree families. Position rules are stricter than McLoop's current\nsubstring-matching behavior: operational tags are recognized **only\nin the leading position** of a task line, immediately after the\ncheckbox and task ID. This is a deliberate departure from McLoop,\nwhich classifies any task whose text contains `[USER]` anywhere as\na USER task. A task description that references the tag form in\nprose (in quoted code, in example text, in references to the syntax\nitself) is not classified as that operational kind.\n\n1. **Flag tags** (`[USER]`, `[BATCH]`): must appear immediately\n   after the checkbox and task ID, before the task description.\n   `[USER]` or `[BATCH]` appearing later in the text is prose, not\n   a tag.\n2. **Action tags** (`[AUTO:<action>] <args>`): must appear\n   immediately after the flag tags (if any) and before the task\n   description. The argument string is the text from the closing\n   bracket of the action tag to end of line. `[AUTO:...]` tokens\n   appearing later in the text are prose.\n3. **Key-value annotations** (`[feat: \"...\"]`, `[fix: \"...\"]`): at\n   end of line. Multiple allowed.\n\nCompatibility mode parses leading tags as tags and treats non-leading\nbracketed tokens that resemble flag or action tags as prose. The\nparser may emit a validation warning when a non-leading token like\n`[USER]` appears inside task text — the warning is opt-in; the\ndefault is silent acceptance as prose.\n\nThe `migrate` operation does **not** auto-promote non-leading\nbracketed tokens into operational tags. Migrating a plan whose task\ndescription mentions `[USER]` in prose leaves the bracket form as\ntext; it does not silently convert the task into a USER task.\n\n`[RULEDOUT]` is **not** a task tag. It is a sibling line at the\nchild indent under the task it pertains to, matching McLoop's\nexisting convention. Reserved for the indent-attached rule.\n\n## 5. Status model and settlement contract\n\nPLAN.md keeps the three-valued checkbox. The ledger keeps the rich\nstatus enum and task-outcome evidence. These surfaces are related,\nbut they are not currently a strict bidirectional invariant.\n\nCurrent behavior:\n\n- Standard code-edit success checks off the task in PLAN.md, then\n  calls `_ledger_settle(..., TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))`\n  (`main.py`, lines 1673-1712). `ledger_emit` emits\n  `commit_landed` only if a git HEAD sha exists (lines 382-425 and\n  subsequent success branch).\n- Standard retry exhaustion marks the task `[!]`, then calls\n  `_ledger_settle(..., TaskOutcome(success=False, abandoned=True,\n  failure_kind=\"max_retries_exceeded\"))` (`main.py`, lines\n  1761-1778).\n- Commit failure calls `_ledger_settle(..., failure_kind=\"commit_failed\")`\n  but does not currently mark the checkbox `[!]` before the terminal\n  failure break (`main.py`, lines 1652-1664). This is a current\n  inconsistency, not a planfile design rule.\n- `[AUTO]` and successful `[USER]` tasks are checked off directly and\n  do **not** currently call `_ledger_settle` (`main.py`, lines\n  1181-1216).\n- Parent auto-checking can mark parent tasks `[x]` as a derived\n  operation without emitting a separate ledger event\n  (`checklist.py`, lines 730-756).\n\nTarget contract after McLoop migrates to planfile:\n\n```\nEvery planfile-mediated task settlement returns:\n  - the new Plan text state\n  - a Settlement describing what ledger event, if any, the caller\n    should emit\n  - whether the checkbox state is direct or derived\n```\n\nThe intended mapping is:\n\n- Direct success with a commit -> `[x]` plus `commit_landed`.\n- Direct success without a commit, including `[AUTO]` / `[USER]`\n  verification -> `[x]` plus `work_observed`. This uses an existing\n  ledger event type and keeps human/automatic verification visible\n  without inventing a task-specific schema before the ledger is ready\n  for `attributed_task_id`.\n- Direct terminal task failure -> `[!]` plus `test_failed`.\n- Derived parent completion -> `[x]` with\n  `ledger_event_required=False`.\n- Resetting `[!]` to `[ ]` via retry -> no ledger event; it is an\n  operator decision to retry existing work, not evidence about the\n  implementation.\n- No outcome yet -> `[ ]`.\n\nThe library exposes a checker for this target contract:\n\n```\ncheck_consistency(plan: Plan, events: list[Event]) -> None | PlanInconsistencyError\n```\n\nThe checker must understand the exceptions above. It should flag\nonly contradictions, not intentional ledger gaps such as derived\nparent completion or explicit no-ledger settlements.\n\nThe directionality stays as it is in the code today: PLAN.md is\nwritten first, the ledger event is emitted as evidence. The library's\nmutation operations (`complete_task`, `fail_task`, `reset_task`)\nreturn both the new `Plan` and a tuple of settlement descriptors:\n\n```python\nnew_plan, settlements = complete_task(plan, \"T-000001\",\n    outcome=TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))\nsave(path, new_plan)\nfor settlement in settlements:\n    if not settlement.ledger_event_required:\n        continue\n    storage.append(build_ledger_event(settlement))\n```\n\nThe caller maps each `Settlement` into a concrete ledger event\n(e.g. `commit_landed`, `work_observed`, `test_failed`) before\nappending. The `Settlement` itself carries only the descriptor\nfields listed above (kind, task_id, phase_id, summary,\nfailure_kind, ledger_event_required); construction of the\nwire-format event is the caller's responsibility, because event\npayloads need run-context (run_id, writer_id, transcript_ref) that\nthe planfile library does not own.\n\nThe tuple form makes derived parent completion explicit: completing\na leaf that also auto-checks its parent returns two settlements\n(the leaf's `commit_landed` or `work_observed`, then the parent's\n`kind=\"none\"` derived settlement). Callers iterate the tuple and\nemit only the settlements whose `ledger_event_required` is true.\nFor leaf tasks with no derived effects the tuple has one element.\n\nThe two writes stay coupled at the call site, not at the library\nboundary. This matches the existing `_ledger_settle` flow rather\nthan fighting it.\n\n## 6. Semantics: `next_tasks`\n\nThe algorithm preserves McLoop's `find_next` behavior. A task is\nactionable iff:\n\n1. Status is `[ ]`.\n2. Every task ID listed in the task's `@deps` line (per §4.2) is\n   complete (`[x]`). Dependencies that do not resolve to a known\n   task are validation errors (raised by `validate_plan`), not\n   actionability blockers; `next_tasks` does not raise on unknown\n   refs. **Contract**: `next_tasks` assumes a validated Plan.\n   Callers must run `validate_plan` before scheduling. CLI\n   subcommands that schedule (`bob-plan next`, `bob-plan done`,\n   `bob-plan fail`) call `validate_plan` internally before\n   dispatching to `next_tasks` or mutation operations; library\n   callers that bypass the CLI must do the same.\n3. No failed (`[!]`) ancestor exists.\n4. If the task has children, return the first actionable child\n   before the parent.\n\nPriority and scoping:\n\n1. Tasks under `## Bugs` have absolute priority over phase tasks.\n2. Within phase tasks, only tasks in the **first incomplete phase**\n   (document order) are returned. Later phases are invisible until\n   the current phase is fully `[x]`.\n3. Failed subtasks block later siblings under the same parent\n   (implicit sequential dependency).\n4. A failed child prevents parent completion. Parent completion is\n   **derived** from children (no independent parent state).\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nnext_tasks(plan, limit=1) -> list[Task]\n```\n\nA `[USER]` task surfaces as \"halt and surface to human\"; a\n`[BATCH]` parent surfaces as one unit (its actionable children\njoined); an `[AUTO:<action>]` task surfaces with its action and\nargs.\n\n## 7. Phase and task identity\n\n### 7.1 Phase identity\n\nThree mechanisms, in resolution order:\n\n1. `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->` comment immediately after the\n   phase heading. **Canonical form** going forward. Already\n   recognized by `ledger_emit.find_explicit_phase_id_for_task`.\n2. Legacy `## Phase phase_NNN: Title` heading. Recognized by the\n   ledger today, but **breaks McLoop's STAGE_RE**. Accepted by the\n   parser for read-only migration purposes; the canonicalizer\n   rewrites to form 1.\n3. Ordinal fallback. The n-th phase heading in document order. Emits\n   a `finding_observed` event tagged `degraded` (current behavior,\n   preserved).\n\n`planfile.resolve_task_context(plan, task_label)` becomes the single\nresolver. `ledger_emit.resolve_phase_id` becomes a thin shim:\n\n```python\ndef resolve_phase_id(*, plan_path, task_label, ordinal_index=None):\n    plan = planfile.load(plan_path)\n    ctx = planfile.resolve_task_context(plan, task_label)\n    if ctx.phase_id_source == \"explicit\":\n        return PhaseIdResolution(ctx.phase_id, \"explicit\", ctx.plan_phase_count)\n    if ordinal_index is not None and ...:\n        return PhaseIdResolution(..., \"ordinal\", ...)\n    return PhaseIdResolution(None, \"none\", ctx.plan_phase_count)\n```\n\n### 7.2 Task identity\n\n`T-NNNNNN:` IDs are mandatory in the canonical form, optional in\nthe compatibility-mode parser. Migration assigns IDs once on first\nparse and writes them back. After migration, tasks are referenced\nby ID, not by text or label.\n\n**Caveat about ledger attribution today**: the\n`commit_landed` event has `attributed_phase_id` but no `task_id`\nfield. Task identity flows through `test_failed.test_id` (which is\nthe task label, per `emit_task_lifecycle_events`). Adding stable\ntask IDs to PLAN.md does not by itself make commits attribute to\ntasks. Two paths forward:\n\n- **Short-term**: McLoop's settle hook maps `task_label → task_id`\n  via `planfile.resolve_task_context`. The ID appears in\n  `test_failed.test_id` instead of the label. `commit_landed`\n  continues to attribute to phase only.\n- **Longer-term**: ledger schema adds `attributed_task_id` to\n  `commit_landed`. Requires a schema version bump; not part of\n  this proposal.\n\n**Caveat about substring matching**:\n`find_explicit_phase_id_for_task` currently uses\n`label_token in line` — pure substring match. This is brittle\ntoday and breaks once `T-NNNNNN:` lands\n(`T-000001` is a substring of `T-0000010`). The library must\ntokenize and match against parsed task entries, not raw line\nsubstrings. Pin in the contract.\n\n## 8. Migration\n\nPhased migration. No big-bang rewrite.\n\n### Phase A: parser-only\n\n1. Add `bob_tools.planfile` with the parser, renderer, validator,\n   and migrator. Parser accepts both old (no IDs, headings without\n   phase-id comments) and new (with IDs and comments) forms.\n   Renderer emits canonical form. `migrate(plan)` is a separate\n   operation that assigns missing IDs and phase-id comments.\n2. `@deps` is supported from the start. The parser reads `@deps`\n   lines, the renderer writes them, validation requires referenced\n   IDs to exist in the plan, and `next_tasks` honors deps when\n   deciding actionability. Minimal scope: dependency graph cycle\n   detection is *not* required in Phase A (a cycle just blocks\n   `next_tasks` from progressing past it; callers detect that as\n   no actionable task remaining).\n3. Add `bob-plan validate PLAN.md` and `bob-plan fmt PLAN.md`\n   commands. `fmt` calls `parse_plan`, then `migrate`, then\n   `save`. Idempotent.\n4. McLoop and Duplo continue to use their existing parsers during\n   Phase A.\n\n### Phase B: McLoop migration\n\n1. McLoop's settle hook calls `planfile.resolve_task_context`\n   instead of `ledger_emit.find_explicit_phase_id_for_task`.\n   `resolve_phase_id` becomes a shim.\n2. `mcloop.checklist.parse` delegates to `planfile.parse_plan`.\n   `check_off`, `mark_failed`, `find_next` delegate to\n   `planfile.complete_task`, `fail_task`, `next_tasks`.\n3. McLoop's parser disappears or remains as a 5-line shim.\n\n### Phase C: Duplo migration\n\n1. Duplo's planner stops emitting raw Markdown. It produces typed\n   `Plan` objects (via LLM-proposed task text, but with structure\n   assigned by Duplo). Duplo calls `planfile.render_plan` to write.\n2. LLM output is validated by `planfile.validate_plan` before\n   write. Malformed output is rejected; Duplo retries or fails the\n   phase. The LLM never owns plan structure.\n3. Duplo annotations (`[feat: \"...\"]`, `[fix: \"...\"]`) are\n   first-class in the typed `Plan` (fields on `Task`), not parsed\n   from text.\n\n### Phase D: cleanup\n\n1. Delete `mcloop.checklist` if the shim has no remaining callers.\n2. Decide whether `commit_landed` should gain `attributed_task_id`.\n   If yes, that is a ledger schema bump, not a planfile change.\n\n## 9. What changes for humans\n\nHumans can still hand-edit PLAN.md. Constraints:\n\n- Editing task text is safe.\n- Editing checkboxes is safe; the consistency check will surface\n  divergence from the ledger on the next run, but does not auto-\n  rewrite.\n- **Do not** edit `T-NNNNNN:` IDs or remove `<!-- phase_id: -->`\n  comments. Either is detected and rejected with a line-located\n  error.\n- `bob-plan fmt PLAN.md` is safe to run anytime: it normalizes\n  whitespace, sorts annotations into canonical position, and\n  assigns IDs to any new tasks. Idempotent.\n\nWhen McLoop refuses to run, the message is:\n\n```\nPLAN.md invalid at line 17, column 5:\nexpected task id like T-000123 after checkbox marker\n```\n\nNo best-effort recovery. The user runs `bob-plan validate` to see\nall errors, fixes them by hand, or runs `bob-plan fmt` for\nstructural normalization.\n\n## 10. Out of scope\n\n- `commit_landed.attributed_task_id`. Mentioned in §7.2 as a\n  future-work item; not part of this proposal.\n- Replacing the Plan Ledger. The ledger is the audit/event surface;\n  planfile is the syntax surface. They coexist.\n- A \"running\" status in PLAN.md. McLoop tracks live state in\n  `.mcloop/runs/latest.json` and a lock file; a crashed run should\n  not leave the plan in a \"claimed\" state.\n- Multi-writer locking semantics for PLAN.md beyond file locking\n  and atomic writes. Concurrent human + tool edits during a run\n  are out of scope; McLoop already prints\n  `\"Do not edit CURRENT_PLAN.md or BUGS.md while mcloop is running\"`\n  on startup.\n\n## 11. Open questions\n\n1. **Should `T-NNNNNN:` be globally unique or per-phase?** Globally\n   unique is simpler for ledger attribution; per-phase makes IDs\n   smaller and locally meaningful. Global preferred unless there's a\n   reason against.\n\n2. **What is the migration story for the four existing PLAN.md\n   files?** (Duplo, McLoop, McLoop's PLAN.EXAMPLE, and any in target\n   projects.) `bob-plan fmt` should handle all four. Verify\n   round-trip on each before claiming Phase A complete.\n\n3. **Should `[RULEDOUT]` move from sibling-line to a field on `Task`?**\n   The runtime behavior is identical (collected and fed to the\n   prompt); the only difference is whether it appears as\n   indent-attached prose or as a structured field. The current sibling-\n   line form survives canonicalization unchanged; the structured form\n   would require a schema decision. Recommendation: keep sibling-line\n   form; treat `[RULEDOUT]` as a parser-collected per-task list in the\n   `Task` object. No syntax change.\n\n4. **How are `## Stage` and `## Phase` headings reconciled?** Both\n   work today and mean the same thing. Recommendation: parser\n   accepts both; canonicalizer leaves them as-is (does not rewrite\n   \"Stage\" to \"Phase\" or vice versa). The keyword is cosmetic; the\n   `phase_id` carries identity.\n\n5. **What about subsection headings (`### Manual verification`)?**\n   Currently used in Duplo's PLAN.md to group tasks within a phase.\n   The parser must accept them. They have no semantic effect on\n   `next_tasks` or `phase_id`. Recommendation: parse as structural,\n   preserve through round-trip, attach contained tasks to the parent\n   phase's `phase_id`.\n\n6. **Is the settlement consistency check per-run or all-time?** The\n   target contract in §5 should start per-run. All-time enforcement\n   would require the ledger to be the source of truth across runs,\n   which contradicts the directionality decision. Recommendation:\n   per-run. Cross-run consistency is an audit command, not\n   `bob-plan validate`'s default behavior.\n\n7. **What happens when a `[USER]` task is checked off without a user\n   prompt?** Today nothing checks; a hand-edit can flip\n   `- [ ] [USER] Verify the menu appears` to `- [x] [USER] Verify the\n   menu appears` and McLoop accepts it. Recommendation: keep the\n   current permissive behavior during compatibility mode. After\n   planfile-mediated settlement lands, McLoop-created `[USER]`\n   completions should emit `work_observed`; hand-edited `[x]` user\n   tasks remain accepted as explicit human assertions and are not\n   rejected merely because no ledger event exists.\n","numLines":755,"startLine":1,"totalLines":755}}}
